The world born on September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001, in the United States.
That day, 19 terrorists took control of four civilian aircraft, crashing two of them into the Twin Towers of the World Trade Center in New York, hitting the Pentagon with a third, and causing the fourth plane to crash in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another U.S. government building in Washington, D.C.
All the hijackers were from the Middle East, and 15 were from Saudi Arabia.
They had all been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American pilot schools, as part of an operation planned, organized, and carried out by Al-Qaeda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
By the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children had been killed, and more than 6,000 were injured.
The majority were American, although citizens from over a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11 had ushered in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaeda followed, including several explosions in Madrid trains in March 2004, then the attack on London’s public transport in July 2005.
Terrorists aligned with ISIS also killed 32 people at Brussels airport in March 2016, and planned a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to ram pedestrians).
However, neither the United States nor any of their allies have ever suffered an attack of similar magnitude to those of September 11 – which are unparalleled.
Therefore, one must question: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference did September 11 make?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why terrorists have not succeeded in perpetrating other major attacks.
Following the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaeda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have put in place procedures that make it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, law enforcement, and military capabilities to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, with terrorism being one of the few areas where states, often in disagreement, are willing and eager to work together to a considerable extent.
There now also exists a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments should not distinguish between terrorists and those who provide them sanctuary and support.
The days when individuals and groups ready to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters are over.
It is not to say that terrorism has stopped claiming tens of thousands of lives every year.
However, almost all attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within ongoing conflicts (primarily in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks like those of September 11 against major powers.
Terrorism is increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
For example, Al-Qaeda survived the elimination of Osama Bin Laden by US special forces in Pakistan nearly ten years after the September 11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no solution to the problem on the horizon.
The possibility of another September 11 cannot be ruled out either, although the U.S. government recently asserted that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country is domestic.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army stated after its failed assassination attempt on British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today we were not lucky, but remember that it only takes one lucky break for us."
You will always need one."
The danger lies in the fact that someday, terrorists will get their hands on nuclear material, or will succeed in manufacturing and using a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could define the era.
For now, that is not the case.
September 11 nevertheless marked a historic turning point, with a profound impact on American foreign policy over the last 20 years.
While the attacks did not lead to a era of global terrorism, they did indeed give rise to the famous war on terror, with major consequences for how the United States behaved around the world, America's image in the eyes of the world, and how many Americans came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Soon after the September 11 attacks, the United States offered the Taliban, who then controlled the Afghan government, a choice: hand over the Al-Qaeda suspects who were about to leave the country and had organized the September 11 attacks, or risk losing their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaeda leaders, intelligence and military personnel from the United States collaborated with an unstructured consortium of Afghan tribes called the Northern Alliance to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
However, this control was never total or uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaeda fled to neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually regained strength and continued to conduct military operations against the new government that had replaced them.
Meanwhile, the United States did not sufficiently work to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, America strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, essentially becoming a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, US intervention in Afghanistan mobilized over 100,000 American soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of operations amounted to over $2 trillion, resulting in the loss of over 2,300 American lives, and several tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The American presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persevering than America, which in 2020 had lost all willingness to fight in a conflict destined only for an indefinite stalemate.
The global war on terrorism also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily if September 11 had not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to want to signal to the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had put it during the Vietnam War, a "giant impotent and pitiful."
This led some members of the administration (chief among them Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which the Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (as most participants later found out he did not).
Others aimed to spread democracy in Iraq, then throughout the entire Middle East, believing that such a move was not only feasible but would also make the region much less likely to produce and support terrorists.
Triggered in March 2003, the war in Iraq did not unfold as the Bush administration, many members of Congress (including Joe Biden, then senator), and world leaders who had approved it had hoped or anticipated.
The United States was not prepared for most of the events that followed.
While initial military victories succeeded in ousting the government, they quickly gave way to widespread unrest and a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs exacerbated an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, like Afghanistan, Iraq demonstrated the limits of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within a reasonable timeframe.
Ultimately, the United States was forced to reinforce their military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 soldiers, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability was achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States spent as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but at a far higher human toll: more than 4,000 American soldiers killed, far greater numbers wounded, and an exploding rate of suicide among American military personnel (from Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total excludes deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for which estimates vary widely, but which number certainly in the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq also weakened the United States in other ways.
No evidence has ever shown Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for military intervention without UN approval – targeting Saddam’s weapons of mass destruction – turned out to be based on no real foundation.
Images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners further tarnished the country's reputation.
Moreover, a Iraq at war with itself became synonymous with Iran emerging as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if Israel is considered).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States were deeply involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted against the United States, both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia and a stronger and more assertive China.
The war on terror could not and did not provide the United States with a compass in their approach to foreign policy regarding renewed great power rivalry.
The wars waged following September 11 also had important domestic consequences for the United States.
They shaken confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War with historically unprecedented dominant power, and undermined national unity that had surfaced immediately after the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars further fueled opposition to a major and sustained global role for the United States, giving birth to a new isolationist trend.
Similarly, this propensity for warfare, coupled with the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, severely impacted American trust in elites, thereby fueling the rise of populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to Donald Trump's rise to power.
Today's America is more divided than ever domestically, and less willing than before to pursue this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, which overall largely benefited Americans and many others.
In hindsight, we can now view September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: less globalization of terrorism than the terror of globalization.
The attacks conveyed the message that distance and borders mattered little in the age of globalization.
Nothing remains local for long now, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis rooted in poor American financial management.
We are all currently facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since it appeared in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves devastating many parts of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself the cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era ushered in by recent events concludes a cycle, marking the 20th anniversary of America’s intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly driven from power; in recent weeks, they have regained it just as easily.
It is too early to know if the Taliban will revert to their old ways and once again become a sanctuary for terrorism, and if terrorists around the world will take pride in their victory over America and its allies.
What we do know, however, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that in turn already determines it.
